NNAAMMEE
       siesh - interactive sieve shell

SSYYNNOOPPSSIISS
       $ siesh \
           --debug \
           --user USER \
           --host SERVER \
           --tls {require|auto} \
           --port PORT

DDEESSCCRRIIPPTTIIOONN
       Siesh provides a shell-like interface for manipulating sieve scripts
       using the ManageSieve protocol.

OOPPTTIIOONNSS
       ----ddeebbuugg|--dd
           Enable debugging.

       ----uusseerr|--uu USERNAME
           Specifies the username to use when logging into the sieve server.
           This option defaults to the value of the environment variable
           "USER".

       ----hhoosstt|--hh HOST
           Specifies the machine to connect to. Defaults to "imap".

       ----ttllss|--tt {require|auto}
           Specifies that TLS is required (require) or optional (auto).

       ----ppoorrtt|--pp PORT
           Specifies the remote port to connect to. Defaults to 2000.

CCOONNFFIIGGUURRAATTIIOONN FFIILLEE
       When siesh is invoked, it first reads configurations variables from
       _/_e_t_c_/_s_i_e_s_h_._c_o_n_f or _~_/_._s_i_e_s_h_._c_o_n_f if one of these files exist. The file
       is structured as a set of lines with name and values seperated by an
       equal sign.

               user  = mario
               host  = sieve.example.com
               tls   = required
               port  = 2000
               debug = 1

       Currently only these two variables are recognized. Values are overriden
       by options specified on the command line.

CCOOMMMMAANNDDSS
       lliisstt
           Prints a list of all scripts on the server. The currently active
           script, if any, is marked by a _* (astersik).

           Synonyms: llss

       ddeelleettee _s_c_r_i_p_t_-_n_a_m_e _._._.
           Deletes a script. It’s not possible to delete the currently active
           script, so please use deactivate first. There’s no way to undelete
           a deleted script.

           Synonyms: rrmm

       eeddiitt _s_c_r_i_p_t_-_n_a_m_e
           Edits a script on the server without downloading it explicitly to
           your disk first. Under the hood it creates a temporary file, puts
           the script content in it and calls $ENV{EDITOR} on it. After that
           the script is uploaded back. It’s also possible to create and edit
           a new script with this command.

           If your script is syntactical incorrect, you will be prompted to
           re-edit the file or throw away your changes.

       aaccttiivvaattee _s_c_r_i_p_t_-_n_a_m_e
           Activates the listed script. User may have multiple Sieve scripts
           on the server, yet only one script may be used for filtering of
           incoming messages. This is called the active script. Users may have
           zero or one active scripts

       ddeeaaccttiivvaattee
           Deactivate all scripts. Deactivation of all your scripts results in
           no filtering at all.

       ccaatt _s_c_r_i_p_t_-_n_a_m_e _._._.
           Print scripts on the standard output.

       qquuiitt
           Terminates the sessiion with the remote SIEVE server. An end of
           file will also terminate the session and exit.

       hheellpp
           Print a short description of all commands.

       ppuutt _f_i_l_e_-_n_a_m_e _s_c_r_i_p_t_-_n_a_m_e
           Store a local file as script on the remote machine.

       ggeett _f_i_l_e_-_n_a_m_e _l_o_c_a_l_-_n_a_m_e
           Retrieve a remote script and store it on the local machine.

SSEEEE AALLSSOO
       Net::ManageSieve::Siesh, Net::ManageSieve

